INCIDENT THAT TRIGGERED THIS:
Task 523 W5 Subtaskmaster entered a 14+ minute forever loop burning 8k+ tokens. Pattern:
1. taskmaster-wait.sh fires WAKE_REASON=MSG
2. SM runs 'doey msg list --to 5.0 --unread' — lists 3 msgs but does NOT mark them read
3. SM re-enters wait
4. Wait hook sees same unread msgs, fires WAKE_REASON=MSG again
5. Infinite loop, no progress

The 3 msgs were subtask_review_passed + two worker_finished — all signals the task was DONE. SM had everything it needed to close the task but couldn't because its wait protocol uses list-only semantics instead of read/consume semantics.

Boss force-cleared the queue via 'msg read-all --pane 5.0' to break the loop.

THIS MUST NEVER HAPPEN AGAIN. User direction: permanent fixes, not band-aids.

DELIVERABLE — THREE LOCKED PHASES:

PHASE A — Audit and permanent fix of the polling-loop class:
1) Audit every wait/polling protocol across the codebase:
   - agents/doey-subtaskmaster.md wait protocol
   - agents/doey-taskmaster.md wait protocol
   - agents/doey-boss.md status check / post-dispatch verification
   - .claude/hooks/taskmaster-wait.sh
   - Any other .sh that invokes 'msg list --unread' or similar peek-without-consume patterns
   - Any agent instructions that tell the agent to 'check messages' without consuming
2) Identify every place that uses list-semantics where read-semantics is required
3) Replace with the correct consuming pattern:
   - 'doey msg read --pane X' (marks as read while listing)
   - OR 'doey msg list --unread' followed immediately by 'doey msg mark-read --ids ...'
4) Update agent definitions (.md + .md.tmpl) so the wait protocol is unambiguous:
   - MUST consume messages on every wake
   - MUST check for fresh work before re-entering wait
   - MUST NOT loop on the same unread set
5) Run shell/expand-templates.sh to regenerate .md from .tmpl
6) Bash 3.2 compat check

PHASE B — Violations detection + logging (observe the pattern everywhere):
1) Create .doey/violations/ directory, JSONL files per violation class:
   - .doey/violations/polling-loops.jsonl
   - (future: .doey/violations/ask-user-question.jsonl from task #522)
   - (future: other classes as they're identified)
2) Detection logic in taskmaster-wait.sh (and any other wait hook):
   - Track consecutive wakes per pane with same WAKE_REASON and no tool activity between wakes
   - If >3 consecutive wakes with identical reason within 2 minutes AND zero tool calls between them → emit polling-loop violation event
   - Fields: {ts, pane, role, wake_reason, consecutive_count, window_sec, session, unread_msg_ids}
3) Hard circuit breaker: after 5 consecutive same-reason wakes, force a long sleep (30s+) and nudge the pane's owner (Taskmaster or Boss) with an escalation msg
4) State tracking file per pane: /tmp/doey/<session>/wait-state-<pane>.json
5) Cleanup: state files cleared on successful tool activity

PHASE C — Go TUI: Logs tab Violations sub-view:
1) New sub-tab or filter under the existing Logs tab in tui/internal/... called 'Violations' (or merge with the Stats sub-tab from task #521 if already built — coordinate)
2) Tails .doey/violations/*.jsonl files
3) Shows:
   - Counters per violation class (polling_loop: N, ask_user_question: N, ...)
   - Recent violations table with ts, class, pane, role, summary
   - Filter by class
4) Reads directly from JSONL via Go file tailing (no cgo, no new deps)
5) Fresh-install compatible (.doey/violations/ created on first session_start if missing)

INTEGRATION NOTES:
- This overlaps with task #521 (stats system with SQLite + TUI Stats sub-tab). Coordinate: the events.jsonl / violations.jsonl format should be consistent. If #521 has already landed, extend the Stats sub-tab rather than creating a new view. If not, define the schema here and #521 inherits it.
- This is the foundation for the daemon work discussed with Boss — flow-keeping daemon will consume these violation events. Event log lock-in matters.
- Don't wait for the daemon — ship the polling fix + detection + TUI now. Daemon uses them later.

CONSTRAINTS:
- Bash 3.2 compatible
- Fresh install works (no manual setup)
- Zero network I/O
- tests/test-bash-compat.sh must pass
- cd tui && go build ./... must pass
- Violation detection must not itself become a polling loop (the great irony would be a bug hunter that burns tokens hunting bugs)

DELIVERABLES:
- Audit report: which files had the bad pattern, what was fixed
- Patched agent definitions (via .tmpl)
- Patched wait hooks with detection + circuit breaker
- Violation JSONL writer
- Go TUI Violations view
- docs/violations.md explaining the system
- Repro test: simulate a polling loop, verify detection fires within 5 wakes, verify circuit breaker caps it
- Task 523 manual verification: despawn W5, confirm it doesn't come back

PLANNED because: architectural change touching agent protocols + hooks + Go TUI + new subsystem. Interview + masterplan phases required. 3 phases can run partly in parallel (A is foundational, B and C can start once A's audit is done).
